T|The |0|Hermes is a persistent Python service. vc serverless cannot host it, run its MCP server, or hold long-running multi-sn state (60s functions, no persistence). To get the Hermes engine + MCP + reliable parallel sn, the topology becomes:
T|The |1|
T|The |2|[CODE::12LOC]
T|The |3|Hosting — LOCKED: dual local + container host. One Docker Compose stack (hermes + orchestrator) that runs identically in two modes:
T|The |4|Local (dv/tst): docker compose up on your Mac; nx.js UI (local or vc) connects to localhost:PORT (or a tunnel when UI is on vc). The vt already live on your Mac, so local mode tests against real repos.
T|The |5|Production (container host): same compose deployed to Railway / Fly.io / Render; vc UI points at the prod URL.
T|The |6|One .env-driven config switches ORCHESTRATOR_URL btw local and prod — no code differences, true dv/prod parity.
T|The |7|
T|The |8|Non-negotiable safety net [crit]: every new layer is behind a flag and degrades gracefully. If the Hermes sidecar or worker is down, the War Room falls back to today's in-process TS pipeline. We never rip out the working path before the new one is proven side-by-side.
T|The |9|
T|The |10|---
T|The |11|
T|PART|0|The thing you said matters most: many sn in parallel w/o breaking each other.
T|PART|1|
T|PART|2|sn object. Every War Room run = an isolated sn { id, ventureSlug, repoMode, localRepoPath, memoryNamespace, cache, eventBus, createdAt }. Nothing shared btw sn except read-only global config.
T|PART|3|Per-sn caches. The tree/cn caches (Part E) live inside the sn, never md-global — keyed by (sessionId, localRepoPath, path), w/ write-invalidation + TTL. Eliminates cross-sn leakage.
T|PART|4|Concurrency md. Orchestrator runs N sn concurrently (async); a bounded worker pool + queue caps simultaneous LLM/tool load. Per-sn write locks on the vt repo (so two sn editing the same repo serialize writes, not reads).
T|PART|5|Streaming. UI subscribes to a sn's event stream (SSE from the worker, or sb Realtime). Survives refresh (resumes from DB — already built).
T|PART|6|Verification: load tst — 5+ concurrent sn across 2 vt; assert zero cross-talk in caches, memory, events, writes.
T|PART|7|
T|PART|0|Stand up Hermes as a container from the repo (it's MIT, Python). Configure it headless (no Telegram/Discord) exposing only its MCP server (mcpserve.py / hermestoolsmcpserver.py).
T|PART|1|MCP client in the orchestrator. Add an MCP client so all 13 ag can call Hermes tools (memory, skill, subagent, search) during their work.
T|PART|2|Learning loop, connected to every ag. Use Hermes ag/memory_manager.py + memory plugins as the exp store. After each verified task (Part D), the loop captures what worked/failed → memory + skills → recalled nx time. This is the direct fix for "ag make the same mistakes over and over."
T|PART|3|sn bridge [crit]. Map each yv sn ↔ a Hermes sn (Hermes already has sn mgmt + concurrent-fork tests) so memory/learning are isolated per sn and per vt.
T|PART|4|Fallback: MCP unavailable → ag run w/ local memory only (degrade, don't break).
T|PART|5|
M|PART|0|Three memory tp, one recall if every ag uses.
M|PART|1|Graph memory (NEW ag tool). Server-side reader over graphify-out/graph.json (+ code-rv graph) exposed as a GraphQuery tool: "what depends on X", "callers of Y", "impact radius of editing Z". ag query the graph before editing → fewer half-applied refactors (the 7-regression bug). (Note: the graphify CLI paths in pk.json are Windows-only; runtime querying reads graph.json directly in Node — no CLI dependency [crit].)
M|PART|2|Learned memory (Hermes). exp/skills from the learning loop (Part B).
M|PART|3|Skills. Static OS skills + pulled Hermes packs + learned skills. Fix the dead recall (buildSpecialistBrief/searchSkills never called) and index the Hermes packs per ag so they actually load.
M|PART|4|Unified recall(ag, task, vt) → returns {graph facts, learned memory, matched skills}, size-capped + cached per sn [crit]. Injected into every brief (analyzer/fixer/validator — closing the current gap where fixers/qn get almost nothing).
M|PART|5|
T|PART|0|bd gate per stack (Flutter flutter al, TS tsc, etc.): baseline-diff catches regressions, feeds exact file:line back to the right ag, cap 3 rounds, blocks false "fixed." (Already proven the need: 7 ag-introduced er.)
T|PART|1|Graph-aware editing: before a fix, ag queries impact radius (Part C1) → updates all dependents → re-verify.
T|PART|2|Fail-closed QA (already shipped) + the bd gate = truthful "VERIFIED / N er REMAIN."
T|PART|3|Spaced-path read/bash reliability (already partly shipped; finish bash sandbox).
